    {
      "title": "Case and Usage",
      "titleArabic": "الإِعْرَابُ وَالاسْتِعْمَالُ",
      "content": [
        "Ordinals decline like regular adjectives - they take the case of the noun they describe: الْكِتَابُ الأَوَّلُ (nom.), الْكِتَابَ الأَوَّلَ (acc.), الْكِتَابِ الأَوَّلِ (gen.).",
        "They can be used predicatively: هَذَا هُوَ الأَوَّلُ (This is the first). Or independently: جَاءَ الأَوَّلُ (The first came). When definite, they require أَلْ or إِضَافَة."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Decline like adjectives",
        "Match noun in case",
        "Can be attributive or predicative",
        "Need أَلْ or إضافة for definiteness"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "قَرَأْتُ الْفَصْلَ الثَّالِثَ (نصب)", "english": "I read the third chapter (accusative)" },
        { "arabic": "فِي الصَّفِّ الْخَامِسِ (جر)", "english": "In the fifth class (genitive)" },
        { "arabic": "هُوَ ثَالِثُ ثَلَاثَةٍ", "english": "He is the third of three (إضافة)" },
        { "arabic": "أَوَّلُ مَنْ جَاءَ", "english": "The first who came (إضافة)" }
      ]
    }
